if I couldn't be sure of your love.

484
01:04:56,166 --> 01:05:03,206
You said you loved me
and that I should take it.

485
01:05:04,333 --> 01:05:07,123
Yes.

486
01:05:08,166 --> 01:05:10,916
I'm sure you lied.

487
01:05:12,458 --> 01:05:18,748
Why? I don't know.
Out of pity, self-interest...

488
01:05:18,916 --> 01:05:25,826
- What self-interest?
- You holding on to this flat.

489
01:05:26,000 --> 01:05:29,250
How can you know what I think?

490
01:05:29,416 --> 01:05:36,076
In fact, I couldn't care less.
You can sell the flat, I don't care.

491
01:05:36,250 --> 01:05:39,540
You said it was better than a hotel.

492
01:05:39,708 --> 01:05:45,748
Not at all.
I said that to make you happy.

493
01:05:45,916 --> 01:05:52,166
That's beside the point.
I want to know why you lied earlier.

494
01:05:52,333 --> 01:05:54,713
Who said I lied? Stop it!

495
01:05:54,875 --> 01:05:58,415
You did. You've stopped loving me.

496
01:05:59,458 --> 01:06:02,208
What good will
knowing the truth do you?

497
01:06:02,375 --> 01:06:04,995
See? You admit I'm right.

498
01:06:05,166 --> 01:06:09,576
I'm not admitting anything.
Leave me alone.

499
01:06:11,750 --> 01:06:15,500
It's true. I don't love you anymore.

500
01:06:19,041 --> 01:06:22,331
There's nothing to explain.
I don't love you.

501
01:06:22,500 --> 01:06:27,170
Why? Yesterday you still loved me.

502
01:06:27,333 --> 01:06:31,373
Yes, very much.

503
01:06:31,541 --> 01:06:35,001
Now it's over.

504
01:06:35,166 --> 01:06:41,916
- There must be a reason.
- Yes, there must be.

505
01:06:42,083 --> 01:06:44,173
What is it?

506
01:06:44,333 --> 01:06:49,543
I don't know. All l know is
I don't love you anymore.

507
01:06:50,583 --> 01:06:53,373
Since we were at Prokosch's?

508
01:06:53,541 --> 01:06:58,121
When you saw me pat
Francesca Vanini's bottom?

509
01:07:01,166 --> 01:07:07,036
Let's say it was that.
It's over now. Let's drop the subject.

510
01:07:09,833 --> 01:07:13,293
Something's happened
since this morning.

511
01:07:13,458 --> 01:07:19,418
It changed your mind about me,
and therefore, your love for me.

512
01:07:21,958 --> 01:07:26,578
- You're nuts, but you're clever.
- Then it's true.

513
01:07:32,875 --> 01:07:39,115
I didn't say that.
I said you're clever.

514
01:07:40,375 --> 01:07:44,665
Was it something I said or did today
that you took the wrong way?

515
01:07:44,833 --> 01:07:46,623
Maybe.

516
01:07:46,791 --> 01:07:51,211
Don't talk to me like that!
I won't allow it!

517
01:08:00,125 --> 01:08:02,415
Camille!

518
01:08:09,125 --> 01:08:12,915
I despise you! That's what I feel.

519
01:08:13,083 --> 01:08:16,173
That's why the love's gone.

520
01:08:16,333 --> 01:08:20,043
And you disgust me when you touch me.

521
01:08:32,458 --> 01:08:35,668
Wait for me. Don't be so dramatic.

522
01:08:39,958 --> 01:08:44,998
Forget what I said, Paul.
Pretend nothing happened.

523
01:09:48,750 --> 01:09:51,120
Good evening.

524
01:09:58,333 --> 01:10:02,583
- Are you going to Capri, too?
- Maybe.

525
01:10:25,541 --> 01:10:28,081
Are you okay?

526
01:11:31,583 --> 01:11:34,623
Mr. Prokosch re-read Homer.

527
01:11:39,541 --> 01:11:44,211
He found something
he had long been searching for.

528
01:11:50,666 --> 01:11:56,536
Something as indispensable
to the movies as to real life.

529
01:11:56,708 --> 01:11:58,498
Poetry.

530
01:12:00,875 --> 01:12:04,705
- You remember...
- Oh, yes.

531
01:12:06,750 --> 01:12:10,580
They say Ulysses came home
to Penelope,

532
01:12:10,750 --> 01:12:14,040
but maybe Ulysses had been
fed up with Penelope.

533
01:12:14,208 --> 01:12:19,618
So he went off to the Trojan war, and
since he didn't feel like going home,

534
01:12:19,791 --> 01:12:22,371
he kept travelling as long as he could.

535
01:12:22,541 --> 01:12:26,291
Do you think it was
an idea of his or...?

536
01:12:36,250 --> 01:12:40,420
- Why do you despise me?
- Leave me alone!

537
01:12:55,166 --> 01:12:58,616
Coming to Capri with us, Mr. Lang?

538
01:12:59,666 --> 01:13:06,036
"Each morning, to earn my bread
I go to the market where lies are sold

539
01:13:06,916 --> 01:13:10,916
and, full of hope, I line up
alongside the other vendors."

540
01:13:11,083 --> 01:13:14,753
- What's that?
- Hollywood.

541
01:13:14,916 --> 01:13:18,036
From a ballad by poor B.B.

542
01:13:19,416 --> 01:13:22,076
- Bertolt Brecht?
- Yes.

543
01:13:31,750 --> 01:13:35,370
Homer's world is a real world.

544
01:13:35,541 --> 01:13:39,001
And the poet belonged to a civilization

545
01:13:39,166 --> 01:13:45,746
that grew in harmony,
not in opposition, with nature.

546
01:13:45,916 --> 01:13:48,536
And the beauty of The Odyssey

547
01:13:48,708 --> 01:13:55,288
lies precisely in this belief
in reality as it is.

548
01:13:55,458 --> 01:13:58,748
Thus in reality
as it appears objectively.

549
01:13:58,916 --> 01:14:05,706
Exactly. And in a form
that cannot be broken down.

550
01:14:05,875 --> 01:14:10,205
And is what it is.
Take it or leave it.

551
01:14:13,666 --> 01:14:17,286
I shut up because I have nothing to say.

552
01:14:30,458 --> 01:14:35,418
I'm not sure about going to Capri.
Where would we stay?

553
01:14:38,458 --> 01:14:41,868
In Mr. Prokosch's villa.

554
01:14:44,333 --> 01:14:49,083
- With your husband.
- And Mr. Lang too?

555
01:14:53,041 --> 01:14:54,921
That's up to him.

556
01:14:55,083 --> 01:15:00,503
Producers are something
I can easily do without.

557
01:15:00,666 --> 01:15:03,746
- Madam.
- Goodnight.

558
01:15:29,416 --> 01:15:34,116
If you don't want to come,
I'm not forcing you.

559
01:15:34,291 --> 01:15:39,871
It's not you that's forcing me.
It's life.

560
01:16:08,416 --> 01:16:11,456
What are you doing?

561
01:16:14,000 --> 01:16:18,290
- What are you doing?
- Looking.

562
01:16:18,458 --> 01:16:22,288
Don't stay by yourself. Join us.

563
01:16:22,458 --> 01:16:27,168
- What were you talking about?
-The Odyssey.

564
01:16:27,333 --> 01:16:32,713
- I agree with Prokosch's theory.
- What theory's that?

565
01:16:32,875 --> 01:16:37,865
That Ulysses loves his wife,
but she doesn't love him.

566
01:16:39,125 --> 01:16:44,955
Do you really think that?
I'm sure you don't.

567
01:16:51,083 --> 01:16:55,873
- Please, you're in the frame.
- Places, everyone!

568
01:17:35,458 --> 01:17:40,998
Are they going to strip off?
Marvellous business this!

569
01:17:41,166 --> 01:17:46,536
You show women in dresses a camera,
and hey presto! They strip off!

570
01:17:59,208 --> 01:18:02,668
Come with us, madam,
leave them here to talk.

571
01:18:02,833 --> 01:18:06,003
No, I'll walk back later
with my husband.

572
01:18:12,000 --> 01:18:17,210
He says you spend all day
with your husband.

573
01:18:19,625 --> 01:18:22,955
Do you mind if you wife comes with us?

574
01:18:23,125 --> 01:18:28,415
Not at all. Go on, Camille.
Go on.

575
01:18:30,916 --> 01:18:36,286
I don't mind, go on.

576
01:18:36,458 --> 01:18:41,118
I'll walk back with Mr. Lang
to discuss The Odyssey.

577
01:19:15,458 --> 01:19:18,418
The girls are in the water, Mr Lang.

578
01:19:18,583 --> 01:19:21,713
I should have done a scene
at the beginning

579
01:19:21,875 --> 01:19:28,495
in which the gods
discuss man's fate, in general,

580
01:19:28,666 --> 01:19:32,116
and the fate of Ulysses in particular.

581
01:20:08,000 --> 01:20:11,830
A producer
can be a friend to a director.

582
01:20:12,000 --> 01:20:17,870
But Prokosch isn't a real producer.
He's a dictator.

583
01:20:18,041 --> 01:20:23,421
I think it's stupid to change
the character of Ulysses.

584
01:20:23,583 --> 01:20:27,253
He's not a modern-day neurotic,

585
01:20:27,416 --> 01:20:33,116
but a simple, clever and robust man.

586
01:20:33,291 --> 01:20:36,251
I find his idea interesting.

587
01:20:36,416 --> 01:20:39,536
It takes Ulysses
ten years to return home

588
01:20:39,708 --> 01:20:43,538
because he doesn't really
want to return. It's logical.

589
01:20:43,708 --> 01:20:49,788
It's logical, and the illogical
borrows from the logical.

590
01:20:49,958 --> 01:20:54,458
Your Corneille said it
in his preface to Suréna.

591
01:20:54,625 --> 01:20:59,285
Ulysses doesn't rush home to Ithaca

592
01:20:59,458 --> 01:21:03,368
because he was unhappy
with Penelope,

593
01:21:03,541 --> 01:21:08,121
but the trouble started
before he went off to war.

594
01:21:14,208 --> 01:21:17,668
He never would've left
if he'd been happy.

595
01:21:17,833 --> 01:21:21,333
The Trojan war was his excuse
to get away from her.

596
01:21:21,500 --> 01:21:25,500
But he killed her suitors, didn't he?

597
01:21:25,666 --> 01:21:29,956
That can be justified
by the fact that, at first,

598
01:21:30,125 --> 01:21:34,325
Ulysses had told Penelope
to accept their gifts.

599
01:21:34,500 --> 01:21:38,330
He didn't see the suitors
as serious rivals,

600
01:21:38,500 --> 01:21:42,290
and didn't want to cause a scandal
by throwing them out.

601
01:21:42,458 --> 01:21:48,998
Knowing Penelope to be faithful,
he told her to be nice to the suitors.

602
01:21:55,833 --> 01:22:02,463
I think that's when Penelope,
who is a simple woman at heart,

603
01:22:03,625 --> 01:22:06,745
began to despise him.

604
01:22:06,916 --> 01:22:11,916
She found she'd stopped loving
Ulysses because of his behaviour,

605
01:22:12,083 --> 01:22:14,543
and she told him so.

606
01:22:14,708 --> 01:22:19,208
Ulysses then realized too late
he'd lost Penelope's love

607
01:22:19,375 --> 01:22:23,205
because he'd been overly cautious.

608
01:22:24,250 --> 01:22:29,460
The only way to win her back
was to murder the suitors.

609
01:22:29,625 --> 01:22:33,075
Death is no resolution.

610
01:24:07,041 --> 01:24:09,121
Camille!

611
01:25:17,416 --> 01:25:21,496
- What a lovely yellow.
- Thanks.

612
01:25:23,833 --> 01:25:26,623
I found this on the boat.

613
01:25:26,791 --> 01:25:30,501
Children shouldn't play with firearms.

614
01:26:18,291 --> 01:26:20,371
Drink?

615
01:26:20,541 --> 01:26:24,581
I was there, outside. Nothing.

616
01:26:58,666 --> 01:27:02,416
I decided not to write
the script you asked me.

617
01:27:05,083 --> 01:27:07,713
Why?

618
01:27:07,875 --> 01:27:11,115
Can l be frank?

619
01:27:15,125 --> 01:27:17,745
Of course.

620
01:27:21,041 --> 01:27:26,621
I'm a playwright.
Not a screenwriter.

621
01:27:31,958 --> 01:27:37,498
Even if it's a fine script...
I'm only doing it for the money!

622
01:27:43,958 --> 01:27:47,788
That's why I'm in a bad mood.

623
01:27:50,333 --> 01:27:55,423
We all have an ideal.
Mine's writing plays. l can't. Why?

624
01:27:57,583 --> 01:28:02,713
In today's world,
we have to accept what others want.

625
01:28:04,875 --> 01:28:07,825
Why does money matter so much
in what we do,

626
01:28:08,000 --> 01:28:10,960
in what we are, in what we become?

627
01:28:12,666 --> 01:28:16,326
Even in our relationships
with those we love.

628
01:28:25,875 --> 01:28:28,665
He is right.

629
01:28:30,000 --> 01:28:33,960
We either do Homer's Odyssey
or we do nothing!

630
01:28:39,708 --> 01:28:43,708
Mr. Prokosch already said it,
you're wrong.

631
01:28:43,875 --> 01:28:46,995
You aspire to a world like Homer's.

632
01:28:47,166 --> 01:28:50,826
You want it to exist,
but unfortunately it doesn't.

633
01:28:51,000 --> 01:28:54,120
Why doesn't it?

634
01:29:01,041 --> 01:29:03,961
You may be right,

635
01:29:04,125 --> 01:29:09,955
but when it comes to making movies,
dreams aren't enough.

636
01:29:16,833 --> 01:29:19,583
When do we eat?

637
01:29:22,916 --> 01:29:27,706
- In an hour.
- Right. I'm going for a walk.

638
01:29:36,625 --> 01:29:39,075
Mr. Prokosch wants to speak with you.

639
01:29:44,708 --> 01:29:49,998
- Is that an order or a request?
- A request.

640
01:29:56,416 --> 01:29:59,206
One must suffer.

641
01:30:01,208 --> 01:30:03,828
That's for sure.

642
01:30:15,416 --> 01:30:17,616
Camille!

643
01:31:03,958 --> 01:31:06,788
It's me, Paul.

644
01:31:12,791 --> 01:31:17,921
Looking at you just now,
felt like the first time l'd seen you.

645
01:31:29,958 --> 01:31:35,288
- Mind if I stay?
- Stay if you like.

646
01:31:55,083 --> 01:31:58,213
Why didn't you speak up earlier?

647
01:31:58,375 --> 01:32:02,535
I don't get you! You always said
you loved that script.

648
01:32:02,708 --> 01:32:08,668
Now you tell the producer it's for the
money, that your ideal is the theatre.

649
01:32:09,833 --> 01:32:14,713
He's no fool.
Next time, he won't be asking you.

650
01:32:14,875 --> 01:32:19,535
How can you not understand
something so simple?

651
01:32:21,625 --> 01:32:26,285
- I bet you'll do it anyway.
- No.

652
01:32:26,458 --> 01:32:31,368
Yes, you'll see. l know you.

653
01:32:33,583 --> 01:32:35,673
I know you.

654
01:32:35,833 --> 01:32:40,713
If I do it, it's for you.
To pay for the flat.

655
01:32:40,875 --> 01:32:44,665
I'll let you decide
whether I do the script or not.

656
01:32:44,833 --> 01:32:48,503
If you say no, we'll leave.

657
01:32:48,666 --> 01:32:52,996
- You're so cunning!
- Not at all. Why?

658
01:32:53,166 --> 01:32:58,916
- If you regret it, you can blame me.
- Not at all! I'm asking you to decide.

659
01:32:59,083 --> 01:33:01,673
You want me to tell you what to do?

660
01:33:01,833 --> 01:33:05,123
- Yes.
- Then do the script!

661
01:33:05,291 --> 01:33:09,211
You signed a contract,
and you're boring me.

662
01:33:12,083 --> 01:33:16,673
- I saw him kiss you earlier.
- I know you did.

663
01:33:19,958 --> 01:33:24,788
- Why don't you love me anymore?
- That's life.

664
01:33:25,916 --> 01:33:29,576
Why do you despise me?

665
01:33:29,750 --> 01:33:34,040
I'll never tell you,
not even if I were dying.

666
01:33:38,791 --> 01:33:43,791
- Tell me or I'll hurt you.
- Why hurt me more?

667
01:33:47,000 --> 01:33:50,040
I have to know why you despise me.

668
01:33:50,208 --> 01:33:55,578
It's crazy! I don't see why
you expect me to accept, anyway.

669
01:33:55,750 --> 01:34:00,080
We need the money for the flat.
I don't want to go back to typing.

670
01:34:00,250 --> 01:34:06,000
I can't accept that after what happened.
Obviously you do despise me.

671
01:34:22,625 --> 01:34:26,785
You knew we kissed and you were
still ready to change your mind.

672
01:34:26,958 --> 01:34:33,038
I turned the job down for you.
So you'd change your mind about me.

673
01:34:33,208 --> 01:34:37,868
Don't touch me.
I don't love you anymore.

674
01:34:38,041 --> 01:34:42,041
There's no way
I'll ever love you again.

675
01:34:42,208 --> 01:34:45,708
Even if I turn it down,
you'll despise me?

676
01:34:45,875 --> 01:34:51,615
- Yes, I will.
- Why? There must be a reason.

677
01:34:51,791 --> 01:34:57,291
- You're the reason.
- What do you mean, me?

678
01:34:57,458 --> 01:35:00,748
I don't know. You're not a man.

679
01:35:01,791 --> 01:35:07,421
Anyhow, it's too late.
I've changed my mind about you.

680
01:35:08,875 --> 01:35:14,165
I know why you despise me.
The other day, when I took a taxi,

681
01:35:14,333 --> 01:35:19,213
you thought I wanted you
to go in his car with him.

682
01:35:20,708 --> 01:35:24,328
And again on the boat earlier.
Don't be stupid!

683
01:35:24,500 --> 01:35:26,790
I have faults, but that's not one.

684
01:35:26,958 --> 01:35:32,958
I'll never forgive you.
I loved you so much.

685
01:35:35,250 --> 01:35:42,210
Now it's impossible. I hate you
because you can't make me feel.

686
01:35:42,375 --> 01:35:45,495
I can! You're almost in tears.

687
01:35:57,791 --> 01:36:01,331
We're leaving! We'll pack up and go.

688
01:36:01,500 --> 01:36:05,960
I'm staying. You go if you like.

689
01:36:06,125 --> 01:36:09,165
Come on, Camille!

690
01:36:10,625 --> 01:36:14,075
- No.
- Then l'm staying, too.

691
01:36:14,250 --> 01:36:20,370
- But Prokosch will throw us out.
- Don't start again.

692
01:37:01,416 --> 01:37:06,286
Dear Paul, I found your revolver
and took the bullets out.

693
01:37:06,458 --> 01:37:09,868
If you won't leave, I will.

694
01:37:10,041 --> 01:37:15,461
Jeremy Prokosch has to return to Rome,
so I'll get a lift with him.

695
01:37:15,625 --> 01:37:19,615
Then I'll probably move
into a hotel alone.

696
01:37:19,791 --> 01:37:23,921
Take care. Farewell. Camille.

697
01:38:02,625 --> 01:38:06,365
What are you going to do in Rome?

698
01:38:08,333 --> 01:38:11,123
Typist.

699
01:38:16,291 --> 01:38:19,041
Me? No.

700
01:38:19,958 --> 01:38:22,538
Typist.

701
01:38:46,625 --> 01:38:51,785
What... do you think... of me?

702
01:38:52,875 --> 01:38:57,165
Get into your Alfa, Romeo.
We'll see about that later.

703
01:38:57,333 --> 01:39:02,333
TAKE CARE

704
01:39:08,791 --> 01:39:13,461
FAREWELL

705
01:40:11,416 --> 01:40:15,036
Nathalie,
I'm leaving for Rome tonight.

706
01:40:15,208 --> 01:40:18,248
Good-bye, then.

707
01:40:59,458 --> 01:41:03,748
Mr. Lang,
I've come to say good-bye.

708
01:41:03,916 --> 01:41:07,286
Good-bye. What will you do?

709
01:41:07,458 --> 01:41:12,168
Go back to Rome, finish my play.

710
01:41:13,291 --> 01:41:16,251
- And you?
- I'll finish the film.

711
01:41:16,416 --> 01:41:20,536
One should always finish
what one starts.

712
01:41:20,708 --> 01:41:23,538
What shot are you doing?

713
01:41:23,708 --> 01:41:28,578
Ulysses' gaze when he first sees
his homeland again.

714
01:41:30,083 --> 01:41:32,213
Ithaca.

715
01:41:33,916 --> 01:41:38,326
- Good-bye, Mr. Lang.
- Bye. l hope we'll meet again.

716
01:41:42,041 --> 01:41:44,671
We're ready, Mr. Lang.

717
01:41:44,833 --> 01:41:47,923
Quiet on the set!

718
01:41:49,541 --> 01:41:52,421
Camera!

719
01:42:44,666 --> 01:42:47,746
Silence!


